In the fourth quarter of FY 2014, NSF made progress in three areas.

&amp;nbsp;


	
		
			
			Human Capital Development:

			
				
				In an effort to measure the acceptance of “data scientist” as a professional category in academia, industry, and government, NSF established a baseline for the number of undergraduate, certificate, and graduate programs in Big Data/data science/data analytics. NSF identified 75 programs in the US.
				
				Inserted language about data science in two solicitations.
				NSF planned to host a conference or workshop of NSF-funded graduate students who are studying data science in FY 2014, but did not receive fundable proposals in time. The conference is now anticipated for FY 2015.
				Developed a mechanism for tracking the applications to the GRF and NRT programs that indicate research interest in data science.
			
			
			
			Partnerships:

			
				Released a Request For Information in the Federal Register (http://www.gpo.gov/fdsys/pkg/FR-2014-09-03/html/2014-20806.htm) with a November 1st, 2014 deadline to explore the establishment of a national network of Big Data Regional Innovation Hubs to scale up the kinds of activities and partnerships established at the Data to Knowledge to Action event. The Request For Information is expected to fund two to four data centers, each of which will develop additional partnerships over their funded lifetime.
				In an effort to measure the multi-stakeholder partnerships created to address big-data challenges, NSF counted 30 such partnerships and 90 partners in FY 2014 through the White House Office of Science and Technology Policy’s “Data to Knowledge to Action” event.
			

			&amp;nbsp;
			
			
			Infrastructure:

			
				Review of DIBBS and BIGDATA proposals continued in Q4.
				In an effort to measure the number of communities/organizations/ecosystems that use data infrastructure and tools for their research and development (R&amp;amp;D) activities, NSF developed a draft methodology to determine data intensiveness of NSF communities. NSF did not finalize a methodology in FY 2014 due to the complexity of the task. NSF is focusing on identifying how NSF programs use data infrastructure and tools to support R&amp;amp;D.
			

