In the third quarter of FY 2014, NSF made progress in three areas.

&amp;nbsp;


	
		
			
			Human Capital Development:

			
				Completed inventory of NSF programs that could appropriately include an emphasis on the preparation of data scientists. Drafted suggested sample language that could be added to future versions of current solicitations to increase emphasis on preparing data scientists. Began dissemination of sample language within NSF divisions leading identified programs. To date, this new language has been added to the new Secure and Trustworthy Computing solicitation.
				Discussed organization of a conference for graduate students who are studying data science with potential principal investigators. Reviewing a white paper outlining conference format and topics.
				Created draft methodology and inventory of Data Science programs within the US, to support future analysis and measurement of the growth of Data Science education within universities and colleges.
			

			&amp;nbsp;
			
			
			Partnerships:

			
				Created draft methodology and inventory of major Data Science research centers in the US, to support future analysis and activities on improving cross sector partnerships within the Data Science ecosystem.
			
			
			
			Infrastructure:

			
				Developed methodology for identifying distinct scientific communities, to support future analysis measuring data science capabilities within different scientific communities.
			
			
		
	


&amp;nbsp;

&amp;nbsp;

In the first half of FY 2014, NSF made progress in three areas.

&amp;nbsp;


	
		
			
			Human Capital Development:

			
				Posted solicitation for the new National Science Foundation Research Traineeship (NRT) Program. NRT encourages the development of bold, new, potentially transformative, and scalable models for STEM graduate training. This year Data-Enabled Science and Engineering (DESE) is the NRT priority theme.
				Generated preliminary inventory of NSF programs that could appropriately include an emphasis on the preparation of data scientists. Identified methodology for refining inventory and for drafting language for solicitations emphasizing interest in preparing data scientists.
				Initiated planning for a Fall/Winter 2014 conference for graduate students who are studying data science. Compiled a list of potential participants of key leaders in data science education.
				Funded and held a workshop on April 11-12, 2014 at the National Academy of Sciences on “Training Students to Extract Value from Big Data.”
			

			&amp;nbsp;
			
			
			Partnerships:

			
				Funded and held a workshop on November 12, 2013 with the White House Office of Science and Technology Policy on “Data to Knowledge to Action.” 30 multi-stakeholder partnerships with over 90 partners were announced.
			

			&amp;nbsp;

			&amp;nbsp;
			
			
			Infrastructure:

			
				Posted solicitation for the Data Infrastructure Building Blocks (DIBBS) Program. DIBBs encourages development of robust and shared data-centric cyberinfrastructure capabilities to accelerate interdisciplinary and collaborative research in areas of inquiry stimulated by data.
				Posted solicitation for the Critical Techniques and Technologies for Advancing Big Data Science &amp;amp; Engineering (BIGDATA). BIGDATA supports research that address critical challenges for big data management, big data analytics, or scientific discovery processes impacted by big data.
			

